        "title": "Cold Open",
        "body": "Between 2020 and 2024, 9,438 people lost their lives on Indian roads because of potholes. That is six people every single day â€” a number that has barely registered in the national conversation. Road accidents overall kill more than 150,000 Indians annually, but pothole-related deaths are distinct: they are almost entirely preventable. The engineering to build roads that last exists. The materials are available. The knowhow is not the bottleneck.\n\nThe bottleneck is a system that rewards contractors for laying asphalt cheaply, penalises no one when it washes away in the first monsoon, and leaves citizens with no practical way to demand repair. India does not have a pothole problem. It has a governance problem."
