        "title": "The Discovery: A Chemical Loop Driven by Nuclear Heat",
        "body": "The Cu-Cl thermochemical cycle â€” developed indigenously by the Bhabha Atomic Research Centre (BARC) in Mumbai â€” offers that third path. The process is elegant in its chemistry. Instead of using electricity to split water, it uses high-temperature heat to drive a closed-loop sequence of chemical reactions involving copper and chlorine compounds. Water goes in; hydrogen and oxygen come out. The copper and chlorine are recycled infinitely. The cycle operates at a maximum temperature of around 530Â°C â€” significantly lower than the 850Â°C or more required by alternative thermochemical cycles such as the sulfur-iodine process. The electrolysis step within the Cu-Cl cycle requires just 0.5 to 1.0 volts, less than half the voltage of conventional water electrolysis. What makes the Kalpakkam facility a world first is the source of that heat. The FBTR â€” India's only operational fast breeder test reactor â€” provides the process heat directly, bypassing the need to first convert heat to electricity and then use that electricity for electrolysis. This direct thermal pathway is inherently more efficient."
