        "body": "The Kalpakkam hydrogen facility is the latest expression of a vision that Homi Bhabha articulated in the 1950s. India's three-stage nuclear programme was designed to work around a fundamental constraint: the country possesses roughly 2 percent of the world's uranium but around 25 percent of its thorium reserves. Stage 1 â€” pressurised heavy water reactors using natural uranium â€” produces plutonium as a by-product. Stage 2 â€” fast breeder reactors like the FBTR â€” use that plutonium to breed more fuel and prepare the ground for Stage 3 â€” thorium-based reactors that would give India virtually unlimited clean energy from its abundant thorium reserves. The hydrogen facility expands this framework. It demonstrates that India's fast breeder reactors can produce not just electricity and bred fuel, but also industrial products essential for decarbonisation. It turns a 40-year-old test reactor into a multi-purpose clean energy platform. In doing so, it validates a broader proposition: that energy security, technological self-reliance, and climate action are not competing priorities. They are convergent â€” and India is proving it with hardware running on the Tamil Nadu coast.\n\n| Parameter | Value | Significance |\n|---|---|---|\n| Max temperature | 530°C | vs 850°C+ for S-I cycle |\n| Electrolysis voltage | 0.5–1V | vs 1.23V+ conventional |\n| Operation | 24/7 | Weather-independent, continuous |\n| FBTR experience | 40+ years | India's fast breeder expertise |"
