        "type": "whats-next",
        "title": "THE BOTTOM LINE",
        "body": "The NEET-UG 2026 episode is not a story of a single leak. It is the story of a system where the guardians of the exam â€” NTA-appointed experts â€” were themselves the source of the leak. Where a father could purchase his son's medical career for â‚¹10 lakh. Where 22 lakh students must pin their futures on an agency that has now experienced major paper leaks in consecutive cycles (2024 and 2026).\n\nThe re-test was conducted. The CBI made arrests. But the underlying question remains: if the question paper can be leaked while experts are setting it, before it even reaches a printing press, what security measure can possibly prevent the next breach?\n\nThe answer â€” whether it is a transition to computer-based testing, a statutory overhaul of the NTA, or a fundamental re-examination of the single-exam model â€” will determine the fate not just of future medical aspirants, but of the idea that high-stakes examinations in India can be fair.\n\n---"
