        "body": "India's official response has been muted but watchful. The Ministry of External Affairs, asked about the Teesta project at a June 26 press briefing, said India was \"aware of the developments\" and would \"take necessary measures to protect India's interests.\" It declined to comment on the Mongla port agreement, saying it was \"a matter between Bangladesh and China.\"\n\nPrivately, Indian officials express deep concern. One concern is the precedent: if China funds a water-management project on a transboundary river, what stops Beijing from doing the same on the Brahmaputra, which flows through Tibet into Arunachal Pradesh and Assam before reaching Bangladesh?\n\nChina's Ministry of Foreign Affairs, in a June 27 press briefing, defended the Teesta project as \"purely for civilian purposes\" and \"in full compliance with international law.\" Spokesperson Wang Wenbin said the project would \"bring tangible benefits to the people of the Teesta basin\" and called India's reaction \"unwarranted.\"\n\n\"The Chinese are very smart about this,\" says the former diplomat. \"They've positioned the Teesta project as a humanitarian water-management initiative. Any Indian objection looks like opposing flood control and irrigation for Bangladeshi farmers. It's a diplomatic trap.\""
