        "body": "The Tarique Rahman-Beijing agreements create a new strategic reality in South Asia that will unfold over the next 12â€“24 months:\n\n1. **Teesta implementation** (2026â€“2028): Chinese survey teams are expected to arrive in Bangladesh within 60 days. Feasibility studies and environmental assessments will take 12â€“18 months. Actual construction could begin in early 2028. India will need to decide whether to engage, object, or accommodate.\n\n2. **BRICS membership path** (2026â€“2027): Bangladesh has applied for BRICS membership with China's backing. If accepted, it would be the first South Asian country to join the bloc after India's founding membership â€” potentially creating friction within the grouping.\n\n3. **Mongla operationalisation** (2026â€“2027): The port expansion will take 2â€“3 years. Chinese commercial and potentially naval access to the Bay of Bengal will become a reality within this timeframe.\n\n4. **India-Bangladesh recalibration** (2026 onward): India will need to assess how to manage a Bangladesh that is more aligned with China while maintaining cooperation on border security, counter-terrorism, and people-to-people ties. The timing is particularly sensitive â€” India and Bangladesh are due to review the 1996 Ganges Treaty in 2027."
