        "title": "The Regional Picture",
        "body": "Bangladesh's China pivot does not exist in isolation. It is part of a broader realignment of South Asian states toward Beijing:\n\n- **Pakistan**: Already China's closest regional ally, with CPEC investments exceeding $60 billion\n- **Sri Lanka**: Hambantota port under 99-year Chinese lease; $5 billion in Chinese loans\n- **Nepal**: Joined BRI in 2017; China-funded projects in hydropower, airports, and highways\n- **Maldives**: Signed free trade agreement with China in 2024; Chinese port investments\n\nBangladesh was the last major South Asian country to maintain strategic autonomy between India and China. With the June 2026 agreements, that era is over.\n\n\"The idea that South Asian countries can maintain equidistance between India and China was always a fiction,\" says the regional analyst. \"The question was never whether they would tilt, but when â€” and on which issues. For Bangladesh, the Teesta was the issue that broke the balance.\""
