        "type": "whats-next",
        "title": "The Bigger Picture",
        "body": "The TMC's disintegration is not an isolated event. It is part of a broader realignment that has left the INDIA bloc in tatters. The DMK exited in early June after the Congress allied with the TVK in Tamil Nadu. The AAP had already left after seven of its ten Rajya Sabha MPs joined the BJP in April. The Shiv Sena (UBT) is on the verge of its own split, with six of its nine Lok Sabha MPs signalling a switch to the Shinde camp. The BJP has declared the INDIA bloc \"dead and buried.\"\n\nFor the NDA, the arithmetic is improving but remains short of a two-thirds majority. The ruling coalition now commands roughly 313 seats in the 543-member Lok Sabha, up from 293 after absorbing the TMC rebels. The target for two-thirds — needed to pass bills such as the Delimitation Bill (the Constitution 131st Amendment), which was defeated in April 2026, or the \"One Nation One Election\" legislation — is 362. Even with potential gains from by-elections in three vacant seats and possible DMK support on specific bills, the NDA is still 17 to 49 seats short.\n\nIn the Rajya Sabha, the picture is more favourable: the NDA is approaching 154-155 seats against a two-thirds target of 163, with the opposition reduced to roughly 63 members. Congress leader Jairam Ramesh has accused Amit Shah of masterminding an \"illegal breakaway\" to engineer a two-thirds majority, pointing to a pattern of opposition splits — AAP in April, TMC in June, Shiv Sena (UBT) threatening to follow — as evidence of a coordinated strategy.\n\nThe story is still unfolding. The Speaker's ruling, the inevitable court challenge, and the looming Monsoon Session will determine whether the NCPI merger is remembered as a masterstroke of political engineering or a constitutional overreach. What is already clear is that on 14 June 2026, the landscape of Indian parliamentary politics shifted — and it may be a very long time before it settles."
