    "body": "<h1>US-Iran Peace Deal 2026: Full 14-Point Agreement Explained</h1>\n<h2>Cold Open</h2>\n<p>On June 17, President Donald Trump sat down at the Palace of Versailles with French President Emmanuel Macron and signed a two-page memorandum of understanding with Iran. The document ended the most expensive four months of American warfare since the Iraq invasion â€” and started a 60-day countdown to negotiate a permanent peace. The agreement followed a devastating conflict that began with Operation Epic Fury on February 22, 2026, when the United States struck IRGC facilities and imposed a naval blockade on the Strait of Hormuz. By the time the MOU was signed, the war had cost an estimated $80 billion, with the Pentagon spending roughly $1.88 billion per day on military operations.</p>\n<h2>The Deal</h2>\n<p>The Versailles Accord is a 14-point agreement that includes an immediate ceasefire on all fronts, including Lebanon; the reopening of the Strait of Hormuz with free passage guaranteed for 60 days; the lifting of the US naval blockade within 30 days; immediate waiver of oil sanctions for 60 days; a schedule for the termination of all remaining sanctions; and the establishment of a $300 billion reconstruction and development fund for Iran. Critically, Iran reaffirmed its commitment not to develop nuclear weapons and agreed to down-blend all enriched uranium on site under the supervision of the International Atomic Energy Agency. The 60-day window is intended to allow for negotiations on a permanent peace agreement, with Vice President JD Vance leading the American negotiating team.</p>\n<h2>Key Provisions</h2>\n<p>The agreement represents a carefully calibrated exchange of concessions. The United States gained an immediate ceasefire, the reopening of the Strait of Hormuz, a firm commitment from Iran on nuclear non-proliferation, and IAEA supervision of enrichment activities. What Washington did not secure was any concession on Iran&#39;s ballistic missile programme, which remains a point of contention. Iran obtained significant upfront concessions â€” sanctions relief, the lifting of the naval blockade, a $300 billion reconstruction fund, and a defined path towards the full termination of sanctions. What Tehran did not achieve was the immediate and complete removal of all sanctions, which remain subject to the 60-day negotiation timeline.</p>\n<h2>Regional Reactions</h2>\n<p>The response across the region has been mixed. Pakistan Prime Minister Shehbaz Sharif, who mediated the initial ceasefire framework on June 13, welcomed the agreement as a diplomatic breakthrough. Gulf states, heavily reliant on the free flow of oil through the Strait of Hormuz, expressed cautious optimism. Iran&#39;s Supreme Leader Ayatollah Khamenei endorsed direct talks on June 18, a critical political signal that gave the MOU domestic legitimacy within Iran. European Union sanctions on Iran remain in place, however, creating a layer of complexity that the 14-point agreement does not directly address. The United States&#39; European allies have indicated they will maintain their own sanctions regime pending further negotiations.</p>\n<h2>Implementation Challenges</h2>\n<p>Within days of the signing, significant disagreements have emerged. The IAEA and Iran are at odds over the schedule for inspections. The status of approximately $12 billion in frozen Iranian assets remains disputed. The timeline for down-blending enriched uranium is yet to be mutually agreed upon. EU sanctions, which were not part of the US-Iran MOU, remain a barrier to full economic normalisation. The 60-day timeline is exceptionally tight, and the history of US-Iran negotiations suggests that every clause will be contested. The Pentagon has requested $80 billion to cover war costs, a figure that contrasts sharply with the $300 billion reconstruction fund offered to Iran in the same document.</p>\n<h2>What&#39;s Next</h2>\n<p>The Versailles Accord is not a peace deal â€” it is an agreement to try to reach one. Technical talks began on June 23, with the US waiving Iran oil sanctions for the 60-day period. The 60-day clock is ticking, and the coming weeks will determine whether this becomes Trump&#39;s Camp David or his Munich. By the August 17 deadline, the world will know whether the Versailles Accord was the beginning of a historic realignment or the prelude to renewed conflict. The stakes could not be higher: a permanent deal would reshape the Middle East, while failure would likely mean a return to hostilities with even greater intensity.</p>\n"
